@node USAGE "Usage"
@toc MAIN
HeadShrink must be used from the shell or other command line (or
ToolManager, DOpus etc.). There are two ways to use HeadShrink, both using
the following format:

@{i}HeadShrink [-options] <from> <to>@{ui}

<from> and <to> should both be files or both be directories.

To operate on a single file, specify the path of the file as <from>, and
the path of the shrunken version you'd like to create as <to>.

To operate on a whole directory, specify the path of the directory as
<from>, and the path of the destination directory (which may or may not
already exist) as <to>.

Warning: Do NOT specify the same path for both <from> and <to>.

The allowed options are as follows:
   -c	Remove C style comments.  These are comments beginning with /* and
	ending with */ which may span multiple lines.

   -p	Remove C++ style comments.  These start with // and continue to the
	end of the current line.

   -a	Remove assembly style comments.  These start with ; or * and
	continue to the end of the line.  Comments starting with * are only
	recognised if the * is the first non white space in the line.  Note
	that this option works with AmigaDOS scripts too.

   -q	Quiet mode.  Only errors are output to the console.

   -r	Recursive scan.  This only applies when processing directories, and
	means that subdirectories will also be scanned.  The directory tree
	will be recreated in the destination directory.

Options can occur anywhere on the command line, and can be combined, eg.

HeadShrink -cpr old_include new_include -q

will quietly remove all C or C++ style comments from the files in
old_include, and put the new versions in new_include.
@endnode

